-- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAppearing in print for the first time in 1558, the book that we know as the Heptameron is the work of Marguerite, Queen of Navarre. The tales of the Heptameron portray the conflicts, ruptures, and upheavals that agitated early modern French society. They are often cautionary tales about the corruption of the late medieval church, about decadent priests and monks, or about the unfortunate faithful whose belief in the efficacy of good works for salvation leads to disaster and death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.1 aBauschatz, Cathleen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConley, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornilliat, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCottrell, Robert D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuval, Edwin M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlidden, Hope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeanneret, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLajarte, Philippe de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanger, Ullrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyons, John D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcKinley, Mary B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKinley, Mary B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRigolot, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 